Auto Regressive (AR) models¶

The previous example demonstrated how to fit Exponential Smoothing family forecasting methods. These methods build off the simple MEAN and Naive forecastors. Another class of forecasting methods are known as Auto Regressive or AR models. The terminology and nomenclature of such models seem like a completely different strategy and procedure. AR models include no new concepts! Those concepts are just packaged differently and often described using other vocabularly. This notebook demonstrates how AR models are just Linear Models and use the exact same assumptions of the "regular" Linear Model we have discussed multiple times. This notebook shows that functions that specialize in fitting AR models manage the tedious data manipulation tasks required to create the features for such models. This notebook concludes by showing how to use Information Criterion metrics to identify the BEST way of formulating AR models.

We will use a dedicated training set consisting of all data through 2016. The measurements for 2017 through 2019 will be reserved as a hold-out test set.

test_series = ready_series.loc[ ready_series.index >= '2017-01-01' ].copy()

AR Models¶

This notebook will not demonstrate the simple forecasting methods. Instead, this notebook jumps straight to the AutoRegressive (AR) models. Please see the presentation provided last week for more details on AR models. Please see, the Rob Hyndman Forecasting: Principles and Practice AR section for additional details. Specific statsmodels AR discussion and examples are available in the statsmodels AR documentation.

AR models are just linear models, but they use a very specific set of features. The features are past observations of the output. The model therefore corresponds to predicting the future GIVEN the past. This is the same goal as the Exponential smoothing family discussed previously. The difference is that we the modeler the specify the exact past observations to include.

The features derived from past observations are referred to as lags. A lag is the prior observation. The motivations for using the lags stems from the lag plot discussed last week. For example, we may wish to relate lag=1 observations. As shown below, knowing the current observation, y(t), tells us alot about the next observation, y(t+1).

In [8]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( train_series, lag=1, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()

Likewise, knowing the current observation, y(t), also tells us a lot about an observation two steps ahead. This is shown by the lag=2 plot.

In [9]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( train_series, lag=2, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()

The autocorrelation plot summarizes just how many lags are relevant.

In [10]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))

sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf( train_series.values.squeeze(), lags=72, ax=ax )

plt.show()

Highly correlated time series will have autocorrelation plots that seem to suggest all lags are important. The partial autocorrelation can help in such situations because it represents the relationship with a lag while controlling for the prior lag. The partial autocorrelation therefore represents a more direct relationship between an observation and a lag. Please see this Machine Learning Mastery post if you would like to learn more about PACF.

In [12]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots( figsize = (12, 5) )

sm.graphics.tsa.plot_pacf( train_series.values.squeeze(), lags=72, ax = ax)

plt.show()

How can lags be included as features in the model? Specialized AR model functions exist to manage this for us. The statsmodels module AutoReg() function is imported below.

In [13]:
from statsmodels.tsa.ar_model import AutoReg

Let's begin with an AR model with 1 lag. The old_names argument is a legacy statsmodels argument. You can safely set it to False.

AR models and "regular" linear models¶

Those two coefficients are the intercept and slope of a "regular" linear model with a single input! To highlight that, train_ar_01_model_fit has a .params attribute just like the smf.ols() fit objects!

We could "manually" fit the AR model by manually organizing the lags! You do not to typically do this, but it is illustrative to see how this works since it highlights AR models are just "regular" linear models! The cell below prints the training series to the screen. The first observation corresponds to January 1990 and has a value of 13255.8. The last observation corresponds to December 2016 and has a value of 16394.3.

The Pandas .shift() method will "shift" the Series "backwards" a defined number of periods. These shifts correspond to the lagged values. The cell below shows the 1 lag values. January 1990 has a "shifted" or lagged value of NaN because the data starts in January 1990. The previous value in December 1989 is missing and so we do not know the lagged value for the initial observation! However, the last lagged value is not missing. The last lagged value is 16260.2. This is the value associated with November 2016. Thus, the 1 Season (month) lag in December 2016 is the value 1 Season (month) prior in November 2016!

More complex AR models represent including more lags as features in the model. The model must therefore estimate additional coefficients (slopes) that multiply these additional lagged observations. Let's manually create the linear model with the lag=1 and lag=2 features.

                          'Employed_L2': train_series.shift(periods=2).values.copy()})

Why does this matter?

AutoRegressive (AR) models at first might seem like a brand new class of model. The terminology is challenging but as you have just seen we can manually create AR models by fittin the models with smf.ols() if the appropriate lagged features have been included. This means:

  • AR models have Gaussian Likelihoods just like Linear Models!
  • AR models have the SAME assumptions about the residuals (errors) as Linear Models!
  • AR models are fit by MAXIMIZING the Gaussian Likelihood which is equivalent to minimizing the SSE.
  • AR models use lagged observations as inputs and assume Linear Additive Features from those inputs.
  • Adding more lags increases the number of features, which increases the number of coefficients, which increases complexity.
  • Adding more lags increases the number of MISSING entries, which decreases the number of complete training cases.

You do not need to manually generate the lags when working with AR models. Instead, you can use the AutoReg() function to manage the process for you. This example was provided to help make it more clear just what the AR model is doing.

The similarities between AR models and "regular" Linear Models are reinforced by the fact that statsmodels includes a specialized diagnostic plot for AR models. This diagnostic plot focuses on the behavior of the residuals. If the assumptions of the Linear Model are satisfied, then the residuals will not have a clear trend, the residuals will not be correlated, and the residuals will have a Gaussian distribution. Do you think the assumptions of the linear model are satisfied for the lag-1 AR model based on the figure below?

In [35]:
train_ar_01_model_fit.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(16,6))

plt.show()

What about for the AR model with 2-lags?

In [36]:
train_ar_02_model_fit.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(16,6))

plt.show()

Forecast visualizations¶

If we are just interested in the forecasted AVERAGE OUTPUT, we can make forecasts with AR models just like the forecasts from SES and Holt-Winters. The .forecast() method requires the number of forecast steps or horizons. One season ahead is accomplished by forecasting 1 horizon.

In [37]:
train_ar_01_model_fit.forecast(1)
Out[37]:

Freq: MS, dtype: float64

Since AR models are just Linear Models, we can also extract and visualize their Prediction Intervals! The syntax for doing so is not as straightforward as the .forecast() method. We cannot specify the number of horizons. Instead, we must specify how to start the forecast and end the forecast with the .get_prediction() method. The documentation for the .get_prediction() is provided below for reference. The .get_prediction() method returns an object which allows the AVERAGE OUTPUT and Prediction Intervals to be calculated.

In [41]:
help( train_ar_01_model_fit.get_prediction )

Help on method get_prediction in module statsmodels.tsa.ar_model:

get_prediction(start=None, end=None, dynamic=False, exog=None, exog_oos=None) method of statsmodels.tsa.ar_model.AutoRegResults instance
    Predictions and prediction intervals
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    start : int, str, or datetime, optional
        Zero-indexed observation number at which to start forecasting,
        i.e., the first forecast is start. Can also be a date string to
        parse or a datetime type. Default is the the zeroth observation.
    end : int, str, or datetime, optional
        Zero-indexed observation number at which to end forecasting, i.e.,
        the last forecast is end. Can also be a date string to
        parse or a datetime type. However, if the dates index does not
        have a fixed frequency, end must be an integer index if you
        want out-of-sample prediction. Default is the last observation in
        the sample. Unlike standard python slices, end is inclusive so
        that all the predictions [start, start+1, ..., end-1, end] are
        returned.
    dynamic : {bool, int, str, datetime, Timestamp}, optional
        Integer offset relative to `start` at which to begin dynamic
        prediction. Prior to this observation, true endogenous values
        will be used for prediction; starting with this observation and
        continuing through the end of prediction, forecasted endogenous
        values will be used instead. Datetime-like objects are not
        interpreted as offsets. They are instead used to find the index
        location of `dynamic` which is then used to to compute the offset.
    exog : array_like
        A replacement exogenous array.  Must have the same shape as the
        exogenous data array used when the model was created.
    exog_oos : array_like
        An array containing out-of-sample values of the exogenous variable.
        Must has the same number of columns as the exog used when the
        model was created, and at least as many rows as the number of
        out-of-sample forecasts.
    
    Returns
    -------
    PredictionResults
        Prediction results with mean and prediction intervals

Extracting and organizing the forecast with the Prediction Interval is rather tedious. Therefore, let's define a function to help streamline the predictions. This function is a wrapper to the .get_prediction() method and manages the book keeping to extracting the forecast trend and uncertainty interval.

In [52]:
def make_ar_forecast(mod, start_step, end_step):
    forecast_object = mod.get_prediction( start_step, end_step )
    
    forecast_df = forecast_object.conf_int()
    
    forecast_df['trend'] = forecast_object.predicted_mean
    
    return forecast_df

Model Selection¶

We can try as few or or as many lags as we want, as long as there are more observations than features in the model. Thus, the natural question becomes what is the best number of lags??!

We need a performance metric to help us identify the "best" model, just as we discussed with "regular" regression and classification problems! Even though we created the hold-out test set, we will only consider the training set performance for now. As we discussed with "regular" regression and classification we must use performance metrics that penalize training set performance based on the number of features. Thus, we should not consider the training set RMSE to select the best number of lags. Instead, we should consider AIC or BIC to identify the best number of lags!

All AutoReg() models include .aic and .bic attributes. We could iterate over many values for the lags and extract the performance metrics. However, there are some slight nuances to properly executing this procedure for AR models. AIC and BIC are calculated by summing the log-likelihood. Thus, their values will depend on the number of observations. As discussed in lecture and demonstrated in this notebook, larger lag values will "drop out" more observations from the beginning of the time series. Larger lag values will use fewer training points than smaller lag values, thus creating an "apples-to-oranges" performance metric comparison.

To overcome this issue, the ar_select_order() function calculates AIC and BIC over the same measurements in all models. Thus, we do not have to worry about higher lag AR models having fewer measurements than smaller lag AR models. The ar_select_order() function ensures a fair performance metric comparison.

The ar_select_order() function is imported below.

In [77]:
from statsmodels.tsa.ar_model import ar_select_order

The optimal number of lags is identified based on AIC in the cell below. We will try up to a maximum of 48 lags.

In [78]:
ar_tune_lags = ar_select_order( train_series, maxlag=48, period=12, ic='aic', old_names=False )

The result is a specialized data type.

In [79]:
type( ar_tune_lags )
Out[79]:
statsmodels.tsa.ar_model.AROrderSelectionResults

The .ar_lags attribute are the required lags that yield the best performance according to AIC. As shown below, the best model requires 26 lags! This is consistent with what we saw in our visualizations. This is consistent with what we saw in our previous visualizations. Using 48 lags produced worse future performance compared to using 24 lags! The ar_select_order() function tried even more possible lags than we considered. Behind the scenes all models from AR-1 to AR-48 were fit and evaluated. AIC (and BIC) are penalizing training set performance in the hope that model performs better on new data.

Summary¶

This notebook demonstrated how AR models are nothing more than Linear Models! Specialized AR modeling functions streamline fitting and making predictions from such models because we do not need to manually create the lagged features!

In [ ]:
